<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-05-14T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-05-14T13:00:00-05:00" n="749" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d749">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002/651: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-05-14T14:00:00-04:00">May 14, 1938—2
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>170. Your 300, May 7, 1 p.m., and Shanghai’s 649, May 12, 6 p.m., Chinese
                            Maritime Customs. After careful consideration of the information and
                            comment contained in the telegrams under reference, the Department
                            desires that you make an approach to the Japanese Foreign Office along
                            the lines of the Department’s telegram 157, May 4, 6 p.m.</p>
                        <p>You may inform your British and French colleagues of your action.</p>
                        <p>Repeat to Shanghai for Hankow.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>